# Rust Backend Standards

## Tauri Command Pattern

- Every Tauri command validates input with serde deserialization.
- Commands are thin adapters: deserialize → call use case → serialize response.
- Business logic lives in `@locus/core` (TypeScript) or dedicated Rust modules — never in command handlers.

```rust
// ✅ GOOD: Thin command handler
#[tauri::command]
async fn create_note(state: State<'_, AppState>, params: CreateNoteParams) -> Result<Note, String> {
    let note = state.note_service.create(params).map_err(|e| e.to_string())?;
    Ok(note)
}

// ❌ BAD: Business logic in command handler
#[tauri::command]
async fn create_note(state: State<'_, AppState>, title: String) -> Result<Note, String> {
    let id = Ulid::new().to_string();
    let db = state.db.lock().unwrap();
    db.execute("INSERT INTO notes ...", params![id, title])?;
    // ... more SQL ...
}
```

## Error Handling

- Use `thiserror` for defining error types.
- Use `anyhow` for internal error propagation.
- Tauri commands return `Result<T, String>` — map domain errors to user-friendly messages.

## Database

- Use `rusqlite` with prepared statements.
- All SQL queries in dedicated repository modules, not in command handlers.
- Migrations are plain SQL files applied sequentially on startup.
- WAL mode enabled; 64 MB page cache.

## ML / AI Integration

- ONNX models loaded on demand, released after idle timeout.
- Whisper.cpp integrated via Rust FFI bindings.
- All ML inference happens on a dedicated thread pool — never block the main thread.
